(set: $advertiserPriority to $advertiserPriority + 1)
(set: $revenue to $revenue + 14)
(set: $trust to $trust - 4)
(set: $fairness to $fairness - 4)
(set: $deadline to $deadline - 1)
(display: "Dashboard")

<div class="warning">
<strong>Advertiser escalation:</strong><br>
Two major advertisers request assurance that their campaigns will not appear near the game. Finance asks whether restriction can happen “quietly before press calls.”
</div>

No one says “remove it because money.” They say “brand safety,” “risk environment,” and “partner confidence.”

The words are softer than the power behind them.

[[Prioritize advertiser safety->Advertiser Priority]]

[[Separate advertiser concerns from content policy->Separate Money Policy]]

[[Continue to final review->Final Review]]


:: Advertiser Priority {"position":"275,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $revenue to $revenue + 15)
(set: $fairness to $fairness - 10)
(set: $trust to $trust - 5)
(display: "Dashboard")

You flag advertiser risk as a primary reason. The dashboard now recommends demonetization and visibility reduction.

The action looks neutral because the form has neutral labels.

[[Continue to final review->Final Review]]


:: Appeal System {"position":"525,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $fairness to $fairness + 8)
(set: $fatigue to $fatigue + 5)
(set: $deadline to $deadline - 1)
(display: "Dashboard")

The appeal page exists. It promises review, but not a timeline. It permits the creator to submit context, but the platform can maintain restrictions during review.

An appeal is not equality. It is a hallway after the locked door.

[[Offer correction path->Correction Path]]

[[Continue to final review->Final Review]]


:: Automation Panel {"position":"525,25","size":"100,100"}
(set: $automationReliance to $automationReliance + 1)
(set: $deadline to $deadline - 1)
(set: $fatigue to $fatigue + 8)
(set: $safety to $safety + 7)
(set: $fairness to $fairness - 5)
(display: "Dashboard")

<div class="box">
<strong>Automated review:</strong><br>
Risk score: 87/100<br>
Flag confidence: High<br>
Recommended action: Visibility restriction + human review.
</div>

The machine is confident, but not accountable. It highlights screenshots, metadata, and keywords, but it cannot explain cultural context, satire, audience assumptions, or harm.

<div class="warning">
“Automation is advisory only. Final responsibility remains with reviewer.”
</div>

That sentence appears designed to protect the system more than you.

[[Trust the score and move toward restriction->Trust Automation]]

[[Treat the score as a warning, not a verdict->Use Automation Carefully]]

[[Check another panel first->Shift Begins]]


:: Compromise Ending {"position":"25,275","size":"100,100"}
(set: $decision to "restricted")
(set: $safety to $safety + 8)
(set: $fairness to $fairness + 4)
(set: $trust to $trust + 2)
(set: $revenue to $revenue - 6)
(display: "Dashboard")

# Ending: The Compromise That Pleases No One

The game remains available, but only behind a stricter age gate and reduced visibility. The studio must replace promotional images and accept clearer warnings.

Internally, the decision is praised as balanced. Publicly, no one reads it that way. Critics call it too weak. Fans call it censorship. Advertisers ask why the game remains available at all.

The compromise works as policy, but not as justice. It manages risk without resolving the deeper question of who gets to define harm, art, adulthood, and access.

[[View final report->Final Report]]


:: Correction Path {"position":"650,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $fairness to $fairness + 12)
(set: $safety to $safety + 5)
(set: $consistency to $consistency + 4)
(set: $fatigue to $fatigue + 6)
(set: $deadline to $deadline - 1)
(display: "Dashboard")

You draft a corrective action option: keep the game available only if the studio changes screenshots, improves warnings, accepts stricter tagging, and places mature content behind an age gate.

It sounds like compromise. It also shifts work onto a small studio while the platform keeps control over visibility.

[[Continue to final review->Final Review]]


