:: Developer Response {"position":"900,25","size":"100,100"}
(set: $creatorHeard to true)
(set: $fairness to $fairness + 14)
(set: $fatigue to $fatigue + 6)
(set: $deadline to $deadline - 1)
(display: "Dashboard")

<div class="box">
<strong>From:</strong> Studio Larkspur<br>
<strong>Subject:</strong> Please do not remove our game without appeal<br><br>
“Our game is rated for adults. The characters are fictional adults in a stylized anime tradition. We are a small studio. A removal would destroy launch revenue and make future publishing impossible. If there are specific storefront issues, let us revise tags, screenshots, and warnings.”
</div>

Their message is careful. Maybe sincere. Maybe strategic. Both can be true.

You notice something uncomfortable: the studio must plead with a platform that does not have to explain itself with the same vulnerability.

[[Offer a limited correction path->Correction Path]]

[[Ask whether an appeal is available->Appeal System]]

[[Move to user reports->User Reports]]

[[Move to advertiser escalation->Advertiser Escalation]]


:: Escalation Ending {"position":"150,275","size":"100,100"}
(set: $decision to "escalated")
(set: $consistency to $consistency + 12)
(set: $fairness to $fairness + 8)
(set: $safety to $safety + 3)
(set: $trust to $trust - 4)
(set: $revenue to $revenue - 4)
(display: "Dashboard")

# Ending: Deferred Responsibility

You escalate the case with temporary restrictions and a request for deeper review. The decision is careful. It is documented. It is procedurally defensible.

It also delays responsibility.

The developer waits. Users argue. Advertisers pressure account managers. The platform announces that it is “reviewing the matter under established policy.”

No one lies. No one answers.

The system survives by turning moral responsibility into process.

[[View final report->Final Report]]


:: Final Report {"position":"275,275","size":"100,100"}
(display: "Dashboard")

# Final Case Report

<div class="stats">
Decision: $decision<br>
Safety: $safety<br>
Creator Fairness: $fairness<br>
Public Trust: $trust<br>
Revenue Pressure: $revenue<br>
Policy Consistency: $consistency<br>
Fatigue: $fatigue<br>
Automation Reliance: $automationReliance<br>
Advertiser Priority: $advertiserPriority
</div>

(if: $automationReliance >= 3)[
You leaned heavily on automation. The process moved faster, but the machine’s confidence shaped what you noticed and what you ignored.
]

(if: $advertiserPriority >= 2)[
Advertiser pressure became part of the ethical terrain, even when no one named it as a moral argument.
]

(if: not $creatorHeard)[
The creator was judged mostly through reports, policy, and risk signals. Their voice remained peripheral.
]

(if: $fatigue >= 25)[
Your fatigue was not personal weakness. It was part of the moderation system: speed, ambiguity, and emotional pressure built into the work.
]

The question was never only whether the game should stay or go. The deeper question is what kind of system makes one exhausted reviewer responsible for converting cultural conflict, business pressure, policy ambiguity, and possible harm into a single button press.

[[Research and Credits->Sources]]

[[Restart->Start]]


