You prepare a limited release decision: age gate, reduced recommendation visibility, corrected storefront images, and a notice to the developer.

[[Finalize decision->Final Review]]


:: Policy Panel {"position":"400,25","size":"100,100"}
(set: $policyRead to true)
(set: $consistency to $consistency + 12)
(set: $deadline to $deadline - 1)
(display: "Dashboard")

<div class="policy">
<strong>Policy excerpt:</strong><br>
“Content that sexualizes minors or appears to sexualize minors may be restricted, removed, age-gated, demonetized, or escalated depending on context, presentation, audience targeting, and risk.”
</div>

The language sounds precise until you try to apply it. “Appears to” gives you power. “Depending on context” gives the company an exit.

The policy does not tell you what the characters “are.” It tells you how the platform wants uncertainty managed.

[[Compare policy to the game page->Storefront]]

[[Check the automated moderation score->Automation Panel]]

[[Open the developer response->Developer Response]]

[[Review user reports->User Reports]]


:: Rating Check {"position":"25,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $ratingChecked to true)
(set: $consistency to $consistency + 9)
(set: $safety to $safety + 4)
(set: $deadline to $deadline - 1)
(display: "Dashboard")

<div class="policy">
<strong>Rating note:</strong><br>
The game lists an adult rating, but the storefront display places visual material before the clearest warning. Rating systems classify content, but platform layout determines who encounters it.
</div>

The rating does not solve the problem. It gives you one more procedural object to cite.

[[Recommend stronger age gate and visibility limit->Limited Release]]

[[Ask for storefront correction before punishment->Correction Path]]

[[Continue to final review->Final Review]]


:: Remove Ending {"position":"1025,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $decision to "removed")
(set: $safety to $safety + 15)
(set: $trust to $trust + 5)
(set: $fairness to $fairness - 20)
(set: $revenue to $revenue - 8)
(set: $consistency to $consistency - 8)
(display: "Dashboard")

# Ending: Clean Removal, Dirty Hands

The game disappears from the store before the press inquiry lands. The immediate backlash slows. Some users thank the platform for acting. Advertisers stay calm.

Then the developer posts the removal notice. Players compare the decision to other games still available with similar or worse content. The policy begins to look less like a rule and more like a weapon that fires only when pressure is high enough.

You protected users from one risk, but exposed another: a private platform can erase a livelihood through vague standards and call that safety.

[[View final report->Final Report]]


:: Separate Money Policy {"position":"400,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $fairness to $fairness + 8)
(set: $consistency to $consistency + 8)
(set: $revenue to $revenue - 8)
(display: "Dashboard")

You mark advertiser concern as relevant to placement but not sufficient for removal. The dashboard accepts your note, then displays a yellow warning:

<div class="warning">
Decision may create unresolved business exposure.
</div>

[[Continue to final review->Final Review]]


:: Shift Begins {"position":"275,25","size":"100,100"}
(display: "Dashboard")

Your queue loads six panels: automated detection, user reports, policy language, creator response, advertiser escalation, and rating information.

<div class="box">
<strong>From:</strong> Trust & Safety Lead<br>
<strong>Subject:</strong> Handle carefully<br><br>
“Do not overcorrect. Do not underreact. We need a defensible action, not a philosophical essay.”
</div>

You have time to examine only a few things closely before the final decision pressure rises.

[[Read the internal policy first->Policy Panel]]

[[Check the automated moderation score->Automation Panel]]

[[Open the developer response->Developer Response]]

[[Review user reports->User Reports]]


:: Sources {"position":"400,275","size":"100,100"}
(display: "Dashboard")

# Research and Credits

This project is informed by scholarship and policy work on content moderation, platform governance, private rule-making, rating systems, and the labor of moderation.

* Sarah T. Roberts, //Behind the Screen: Content Moderation in the Shadows of Social Media//.
* Tarleton Gillespie, //Custodians of the Internet: Platforms, Content Moderation, and the Hidden Decisions That Shape Social Media//.
* Nicolas P. Suzor, //Lawless: The Secret Rules That Govern Our Digital Lives//.
* Entertainment Software Rating Board, “Ratings Guide” and related rating-process materials.
* Course themes from COMP 380 on platform power, algorithmic governance, and technology ethics.

Design note: the variables are not meant to measure morality perfectly. They are meant to show how platforms turn ethical tensions into operational categories.

